Adios to the=C2=A0134 Not Boring people=C2=A0who left us since last week (l=
otta New Year inbox cleaning!). If you haven=E2=80=99t subscribed, join=C2=
=A0218,707 smart, curious folks by subscribing here:
Today=E2=80=99s Not Boring is brought to you by=E2=80=A6 Plaid [ https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/4cd01f1f-f862-42e2-8c97-098a142fa575?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3=
QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
You may know Plaid [ https://substack.com/redirect/4cd01f1f-f862-42e2-8c97-=
098a142fa575?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Exk=
RNpU ] as the company that lets you safely and quickly connect your bank to=
 your favorite finance apps. When their original product dropped back in 20=
13, it was like magic and unleashed a whole wave of fintech innovation =E2=
=80=93 think Venmo, Chime, and SoFi. Ten years later, Plaid has established=
 itself as one of the leading digital finance platforms and has rolled out =
a whole suite of products that allow businesses to get the most out of thei=
r financial data - including payments, identity verification, and credit.
Now, Plaid just dropped its 2023 Fintech Effect report =E2=80=93 a 2,000 pe=
rson survey on everything important happening in fintech. The report combin=
es the survey=E2=80=99s results and Plaid=E2=80=99s unique vantage point in=
 the industry to produce a comprehensive overview over everything you need =
to to know about building in fintech in 2023. The best part? It=E2=80=99s c=
ompletely free.
If you=E2=80=99re a founder, builder, investor, or just curious about the f=
uture of money =E2=80=93 then do yourself a favor and spend a few moments d=
iving deep into the 2023 Fintech Effect.=C2=A0
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Last week, I wrote about [ https://substack.com/redirect/121de677-a846-4e3e=
-97e0-49af90841adc?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU ] Stewart Brand=E2=80=99s Pace Layers [ https://substack.com/red=
irect/87aced50-d169-45e0-8518-bcf00921087d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7Gn=
A_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. I said I=E2=80=99d probably be using =
them as a framework going forward, and that I=E2=80=99d call out which laye=
r I was writing about when I did.=C2=A0
We didn=E2=80=99t have to wait long. This week, I=E2=80=99m writing about t=
he beautiful messiness at my favorite layer: the fashion layer.=C2=A0
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.=C2=A0
The Experimentation Layer
Last week, Rabbit [ https://substack.com/redirect/7f8e9c58-f25c-4793-83f2-8=
fd6b8700e88?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ] dropped its $199 AI device, the r1.=C2=A0
It sold out 40,000 devices across four pre-order batches, good for $8 milli=
on in booked revenue, tout de suite. It also launched a thousand tweets arg=
uing that =E2=80=9Cit should have been an app,=E2=80=9D that it would never=
 work at $199, that it didn=E2=80=99t have a real use case, and that it was=
 a solution in search of a problem.=C2=A0
Look, I don=E2=80=99t know the Rabbit founders, they don=E2=80=99t need me =
to defend them, and they=E2=80=99re laughing all the way to the bank as we =
speak. But some of the reactions to the product are the latest in a long li=
ne of commentary I=E2=80=99ve noticed that amounts to:=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CWhy didn=E2=80=99t they simply do the perfect thing on the first a=
ttempt?=E2=80=9D
The short answer is: that=E2=80=99s not how this works. Things are not line=
ar or clean. We can only asymptote towards perfection through trial and err=
or.=C2=A0
Even Steve Jobs, the Steve Jobs, launched the ROKR E1 in partnership with M=
otorola before the iPhone, as Michael Mofina pointed out to me [ https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/0284a6d0-1c00-4643-96a3-2b74ff8c204a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3=
QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. I had memory holed it. =
It was a total bust.=C2=A0
=C2=A0You don=E2=80=99t have to watch that whole video, but if you want a l=
ittle hit of cringe, start at 10:50, where Steve lets the COO of Cingular W=
ireless come onstage to do a corporate standup comedy routine. No one gets =
this stuff right every time, not even ~*Steve*~.=C2=A0
The longer answer, which we=E2=80=99ll explore today, is that the beauty of=
 the system lies in millions of people trying new things, most of which wil=
l fail outright, some of which will succeed spectacularly, and many of whic=
h will survive only in pieces, contributing a new mechanism, concept, or fe=
ature to the pile of Lego bricks that the next group of tinkerers can play =
with.=C2=A0
This is true for products, research, and ideas, even the ones you disagree =
with. Especially the ones you disagree with.=C2=A0
The point isn=E2=80=99t to play it safe and get it right the first time; if=
 any one person or group of people had The Answers, we might as well give r=
eal communism a try.=C2=A0
The point is to experiment with wild, clever, creative, novel things, get f=
eedback from the market, and iterate until, maybe, something emerges that i=
mproves society in a fundamental way.=C2=A0
Let=E2=80=99s turn to the Pace Layers [ https://substack.com/redirect/121de=
677-a846-4e3e-97e0-49af90841adc?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjm=
lXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=C2=A0
The Experimentation Layer
I like to think of the top layer of Stewart Brand=E2=80=99s Pace Layers [ h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/121de677-a846-4e3e-97e0-49af90841adc?j=3DeyJ1I=
joiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the fashion la=
yer, as the Experimentation Layer.=C2=A0=C2=A0
This is my favorite layer, the fuel that keeps the engine of progress hummi=
ng, the raw material from which society is sculpted. It=E2=80=99s where new=
 things and ideas come to play, airlocked from hurting the deeper levels, f=
ree to compete for the right to change them for the better. As Brand writes=
 (modified with our new name):=C2=A0
The job of experimentation is to be froth=E2=80=94quick, irrelevant, engagi=
ng, self-preoccupied, and cruel. Try this! No, no, try this! It is culture =
cut free to experiment as creatively and irresponsibly as the society can b=
ear. From all that variety comes driving energy for commerce (the annual mo=
del change in automobiles) and the occasional good idea or practice that si=
fts down to improve deeper levels.
Most of the things that get tried out at the experimentation layer don=E2=
=80=99t make it through. Clothes go out of style, ideas crumble in the face=
 of scrutiny, radical campaigns lose, and there=E2=80=99s that at-least-dir=
ectionally-correct stat that 90% of startups fail. That=E2=80=99s OK. That=
=E2=80=99s great!
Variance is the point. Launch a million mutations and see which increases s=
ociety=E2=80=99s fitness. If something seems too unpolished, ambitious, wei=
rd, or even dangerous, good! It=E2=80=99s in the right place.=C2=A0
Capitalism=E2=80=99s main advantage over other economic systems is that the=
 experimentation layer exists within capitalism, and does not exist within =
other economic systems. Democracy=E2=80=99s main advantage over other gover=
nance systems is that the experimentation layer exists within democracy, an=
d does not exist within other governance systems.=C2=A0
Stalin skipped this layer and went straight for commerce or infrastructure =
or culture. Empirically, that didn=E2=80=99t work.=C2=A0
A society needs a lot of wild, crazy new ideas to fight off stagnation, to =
grow and evolve, even if each particular wild, crazy new idea seems jarring=
, scary, incomplete, or impractical. For better or worse, the froth is what=
 produces the occasional good idea or practice that sifts down to improve d=
eeper levels.=C2=A0
There doesn=E2=80=99t seem to be a reliable shortcut, as nice as it would b=
e if there were.=C2=A0
There are a couple of ways a new idea can sift down to improve the deeper l=
evels: in full or in part. We can look at startups as an example.=C2=A0
Two Paths to the Deeper Layers
The first path is to make it through fully-formed; altered a little, sure, =
but intact in the form of a company that survives the early stages of start=
up life to become part of the fabric of commerce, something a lot of people=
 pay for and use every day.=C2=A0
This is the path to riches and glory. Zuckerberg walked this path. Musk wal=
ked this path. Bezos walked this path. It takes a lot: new ideas, fortitude=
, timing, adaptability, drive, and all of the other attributes attributed t=
o successful entrepreneurs.
The second path is to create an idea, mechanism, feature, or whatever that =
is so novel and unique that it survives and eventually sifts down on the ba=
ck of another product, even if the company that created it fails.=C2=A0
This is the less appreciated and often derided path, the path to on-paper f=
ailure but potentially lasting legacy, like passing on good genes to your k=
ids and watching them succeed in ways you couldn=E2=80=99t.=C2=A0
But this group contributes as much to the world=E2=80=99s progress as the f=
ormer. It should be celebrated for its sacrifices, and potentially even rew=
arded posthumously.=C2=A0
There should be Retroactive Public Goods Funding [ https://substack.com/red=
irect/3df94b66-e878-48b8-8810-a71803889d64?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7Gn=
A_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] for those founders crazy enough to try=
 something truly new that failed as a business but succeeded in creating us=
eful mutations, maybe even ticker tape parades, and certainly not derision.=
=20
Venture capital actually does a pretty great job here (the beauty of the mo=
del is a subject for a future piece, but we need do more to create the cond=
itions for even more wild experiments =E2=80=94 from the garage to the lab =
=E2=80=94 because they create the ingredients for progress.=20
Without those on-paper failures, future on-paper successes would be less li=
kely.=C2=A0
The only real failure is failing without adding anything new to the stew.=
=C2=A0
Experimentation Everywhere
I=E2=80=99m using startups as an example here, but this is true for anythin=
g =E2=80=93 new ideas, new research, new political ideologies.=C2=A0
And it operates at different scales. For instance, some nations are experim=
enting with radical new economic models like stringent degrowth policies or=
 near anarcho-capitalism. If you live in Germany or Argentina, you might no=
t love that your leaders are running opposite experiments on your country, =
but from a global perspective, it=E2=80=99s truly fascinating to get to tes=
t degrowth and anarcho-capitalism in production.=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0
Whatever the specific situation, people want new things to look like this:=
=C2=A0
But that is the least valuable kind of new thing there is!=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s launching yet another ChatGPT wrapper as an app, doing resea=
rch that=E2=80=99s likely to get funded, running a safe campaign by saying =
what the voters want to hear. It might even work in the short-term, but it =
doesn=E2=80=99t move the needle.=C2=A0
The lower layers =E2=80=93 commerce, infrastructure, governance, culture, a=
nd nature =E2=80=93 are for slow and steady. They=E2=80=99re the backstop. =
The experimentation layer is for froth and novelty and things that are like=
ly to fail but might, just might, echo down into the deeper layers.=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99ve written about society=E2=80=99s relatively recent risk aversio=
n [ https://substack.com/redirect/f1f92643-a99b-4282-8886-34fedaaee7b3?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] a bunch, a=
nd the more I think about it, the more I think that a big part of the issue=
 is trying to smooth the experimentation layer into a straight line.=C2=A0
This can show up as silly things, like telling hardware developers that the=
y should have built an app instead [ https://substack.com/redirect/df4d973e=
-653b-4b0b-b4ba-c88858788d70?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXX=
epKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. It can show up as a scientific research system that=
 funds safe, incremental work instead of crazy new ideas =E2=80=93 81% of F=
ast Grants recipients who responded to a survey [ https://substack.com/redi=
rect/d79cf09d-b273-488f-acf0-7165ed0e28e2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA=
_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] said that their research programs would=
 become more ambitious if they could choose how to spend their funding. It =
shows up in the ideas that people aren=E2=80=99t allowed to discuss without=
 getting canceled.=C2=A0
The effect is that of an overactive immune system that starts attacking its=
 own cells.=C2=A0
So when people try something new, or introduce a radical idea, the experien=
ce looks something like this:=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s part of the process, too, of course. For something to escape=
 the experimentation layer and influence the deeper, slower layers, it need=
s to survive the gauntlet.
Trust the Layers=C2=A0
I wonder if, given the declining trust in institutions further down the sta=
ck [ https://substack.com/redirect/321d0e9e-b650-4c29-b082-7ceca2bf293e?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], people=
 feel the need to police new things at the experimentation layer, just as a=
 basketball team without a dominant rim protector might play a safer, less =
aggressive defense on the perimeter.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CWhat happens,=E2=80=9D they seem to ask, =E2=80=9Cif we let a bad =
idea slip through?=E2=80=9D
The more important, and harder to predict, question is, =E2=80=9CWhat happe=
ns if we choke the good ideas out before they have a chance to sift down?=
=E2=80=9D
There=E2=80=99s good news though: the experimentation layer seems to be get=
ting unshackled. In my conversations and adventures on the internet, I=E2=
=80=99ve noticed the tide turning. Maybe you=E2=80=99ve felt the vibe shift=
, too.
From the ashes of institutional trust a phoenix of trust in people to make =
up their own minds is rising.=C2=A0
Throwing everyone together, online, 24/7, and giving them information and a=
ccess to each other directly, unfiltered, was bound to have a jarring impac=
t. It=E2=80=99s become clear that no one =E2=80=93 not politicians, not the=
 smartest person you know =E2=80=93 has all The Answers, and we=E2=80=99re =
learning how to live in a world where that=E2=80=99s evident.=C2=A0
Instead of trust in any one person or group of people=E2=80=99s opinions at=
 the experimentation layer, we can trust that the deeper layers will provid=
e a backstop, and free the experimentation layer up for maximal variance.=
=20
A few examples:=20
Controversial ideas aren=E2=80=99t as likely to get you canceled anymore. T=
he Overton Window seems to be expanding. Just this weekend, Moment of Zen i=
nterviewed Curtis Yarvin [ https://substack.com/redirect/b5327252-6a04-47d0=
-9441-8b6f86cac11a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU ]. I don=E2=80=99t know Yarvin=E2=80=99s ideas well enough to sa=
y which I agree with and disagree with, but airing them out and letting peo=
ple decide which to incorporate and which to dismiss for themselves feels l=
ike a healthy step. It=E2=80=99s been said before, but X under Elon has pla=
yed a role here, and I think it=E2=80=99s a positive development.=C2=A0
Crypto is coming back, using the building blocks from the last cycle to cre=
ate something about which Larry Fink, the head of world=E2=80=99s largest a=
sset manager, BlackRock, said: =E2=80=9CWe believe the next step going forw=
ard will be the tokenization of financial assets. [ https://substack.com/re=
direct/be864233-a656-4cc5-99c7-3ffbf7950b7b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7G=
nA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=E2=80=9D
People want the tokenization of financial assets, proof of personhood, and =
stablecoins without monkey jpegs, memecoins, and friend.tech, but I guess t=
he point I=E2=80=99m trying to make is that you don=E2=80=99t get the token=
ization of financial assets, proof of personhood, and stablecoins without m=
onkey jpegs, memecoins, and friend.tech.=C2=A0
This meme only ever makes sense with the benefit of hindsight:
These are just a few examples, but there are many. You can probably name a =
bunch. And then there=E2=80=99s Rabbit.=C2=A0
The market quickly drowned out Rabbit=E2=80=99s naysayers; now it will be u=
p to Rabbit to make it through the experimentation layer or die trying.=C2=
=A0
Maybe Rabbit makes it through fully formed, iterating across new versions t=
o eventually topple Apple. Maybe it fizzles. Maybe a big company or young e=
ntrepreneur riffs on one or two of its features and adds their own twist to=
 create the next big thing.=C2=A0
I don=E2=80=99t know how it will turn out. No one knows how it will turn ou=
t. You really do need to fuck around to find out.=C2=A0
Here=E2=80=99s to the crazy ones.
Thanks to Dan [ https://substack.com/redirect/e126f2e2-cacc-4063-b522-e42d8=
b9c14ef?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
] for editing!
That=E2=80=99s all for today. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox with a We=
ekly Dose on Friday.
Thanks for reading,
Packy

